# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: autohotkey
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] AutoHotkey was initially released by its creator, Chris Mallet, in 2003; it has subsequently become one of the most commonly used and commonly recommended pieces of software available for simple macro implementation.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] The installation package includes an extensive help file; web-based documentation is also available.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] AutoHotkey scripts can be used to launch programs, open documents, and emulate keystrokes or mouse clicks and movements.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] They can also assign, retrieve, and manipulate variables, run loops, and manipulate windows, files, and folders.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] They can be triggered by a hotkey, such as a script that opens an internet browser when the user presses the relevant hotkey (key combination) Ctrl+Alt+I on the keyboard.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] AutoHotkey also allows "hotstrings" that automatically replace certain text as it is typed, such as assigning the string "btw" to produce the text "by the way", or the text "%o" to produce "percentage of".
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] Keyboard keys can also be remapped and disabled—for example, so that pressing Ctrl+M produces an em dash in the active window.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] Scripts can also be set to run automatically at computer startup, with no keyboard action required—for example, for performing file management at a set interval.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] More complex tasks can be achieved with custom data entry forms (GUI windows), working with the system registry, or using the Windows API by calling functions from DLLs.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] The scripts can be compiled into standalone executable files that can be run on other computers without AutoHotkey installed.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] The C++ source code can be compiled with Visual Studio Express.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] AutoHotkey allows memory access through pointers, as in C.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] The first public beta of AutoHotkey was released on November 10, 2003, after author Chris Mallett's proposal to integrate hotkey support into AutoIt v2 failed to generate response from the AutoIt community.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] Mallett built a new program from scratch basing the syntax on AutoIt v2 and using AutoIt v3 for some commands and the compiler.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] Later, AutoIt v3 switched from GPL to closed source because of "other projects repeatedly taking AutoIt code" and "setting themselves up as competitors".
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] In 2010, AutoHotkey v1.1 (originally called AutoHotkey_L) became the platform for ongoing development of AutoHotkey.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] In late 2012, it became the official branch.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] Another port of the program is AutoHotkey.dll.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] A well known fork of the program is AutoHotkey_H, which has its own subforum on the main site.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] In July 2021, the first AutoHotkey v2 beta was released.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] The first release candidate was released on November 20, 2022, with the full release of v2.0.0 planned later in the year.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] On December 20, 2022, version 2.0.0 was officially released.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] On January 22, 2023, AutoHotkey v2 became the official primary version.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] AutoHotkey v1.1 became legacy and no new features were implemented, but this version was still supported by the site.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] On March 16, 2024, the final update of AutoHotkey v1.1 was released.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] AutoHotkey v1.1 has now reached its end of life (this version has been "deprecated").
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] The following script searches for a particular word or phrase using Google.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] After the user copies text from any application to the clipboard, pressing the configurable hotkey ⊞ Win+G opens the user's default web browser and performs the search.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] When AutoHotkey is used to make standalone software for distribution, that software must include the part of AutoHotkey itself that understands and executes AutoHotkey scripts, as it is an interpreted language.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] Inevitably, some malware has been written using AutoHotkey.
[src:autohotkey/autohotkey] When anti-malware products attempt to earmark items of malware that have been programmed using AutoHotkey, they sometimes falsely identify AutoHotkey as the culprit rather than the actual malware.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Automation includes the use of various equipment and control systems such as machinery, processes in factories, boilers, and heat-treating ovens, switching on telephone networks, steering, stabilization of ships, aircraft and other applications and vehicles with reduced human intervention.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Examples range from a household thermostat controlling a boiler to a large industrial control system with tens of thousands of input measurements and output control signals.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] In the simplest type of an automatic control loop, a controller compares a measured value of a process with a desired set value and processes the resulting error signal to change some input to the process, in such a way that the process stays at its set point despite disturbances.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] This closed-loop control is an application of negative feedback to a system.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The mathematical basis of control theory began in the 18th century and advanced rapidly in the 20th.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The term *automation*, inspired by the earlier word *automatic* (coming from *automaton*), was not widely used before 1947, when Ford established an automation department.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] It was during this time that the industry was rapidly adopting feedback controllers, Technological advancements introduced in the 1930s revolutionized various industries significantly.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The World Bank's World Development Report of 2019 shows evidence that the new industries and jobs in the technology sector outweigh the economic effects of workers being displaced by automation.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Job losses and downward mobility blamed on automation have been cited as one of many factors in the resurgence of nationalist, protectionist and populist politics in the US, UK and France, among other countries since the 2010s.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] It was a preoccupation of the Greeks and Arabs (in the period between about 300 BC and about 1200 AD) to keep an accurate track of time.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] In Ptolemaic Egypt, about 270 BC, Ctesibius described a float regulator for a water clock, a device not unlike the ball and cock in a modern flush toilet.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] This was the earliest feedback-controlled mechanism.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The appearance of the mechanical clock in the 14th century made the water clock and its feedback control system obsolete.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The Persian Banū Mūsā brothers, in their *Book of Ingenious Devices* (850 AD), described a number of automatic controls.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Two-step level controls for fluids, a form of discontinuous variable structure controls, were developed by the Banu Musa brothers.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] They also described a feedback controller.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The design of feedback control systems up through the Industrial Revolution was by trial-and-error, together with a great deal of engineering intuition.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] It was not until the mid-19th century that the stability of feedback control systems was analyzed using mathematics, the formal language of automatic control theory.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was invented by Christiaan Huygens in the seventeenth century, and used to adjust the gap between millstones.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Another control mechanism was used to tent the sails of windmills.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Also in 1745, Jacques de Vaucanson invented the first automated loom.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Around 1800, Joseph Marie Jacquard created a punch-card system to program looms.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] In 1771 Richard Arkwright invented the first fully automated spinning mill driven by water power, known at the time as the water frame.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] An automatic flour mill was developed by Oliver Evans in 1785, making it the first completely automated industrial process.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Bunce of England in 1784 as part of a model steam crane.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was adopted by James Watt for use on a steam engine in 1788 after Watt's partner Boulton saw one at a flour mill Boulton & Watt were building.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The governor could not actually hold a set speed; the engine would assume a new constant speed in response to load changes.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The governor was able to handle smaller variations such as those caused by fluctuating heat load to the boiler.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Also, there was a tendency for oscillation whenever there was a speed change.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] As a consequence, engines equipped with this governor were not suitable for operations requiring constant speed, such as cotton spinning.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Several improvements to the governor, plus improvements to valve cut-off timing on the steam engine, made the engine suitable for most industrial uses before the end of the 19th century.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Advances in the steam engine stayed well ahead of science, both thermodynamics and control theory.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The governor received relatively little scientific attention until James Clerk Maxwell published a paper that established the beginning of a theoretical basis for understanding control theory.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Relay logic was introduced with factory electrification, which underwent rapid adaptation from 1900 through the 1920s.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Central electric power stations were also undergoing rapid growth and the operation of new high-pressure boilers, steam turbines and electrical substations created a great demand for instruments and controls.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Central control rooms became common in the 1920s, but as late as the early 1930s, most process controls were on-off.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Operators typically monitored charts drawn by recorders that plotted data from instruments.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] To make corrections, operators manually opened or closed valves or turned switches on or off.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Control rooms also used color-coded lights to send signals to workers in the plant to manually make certain changes.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The development of the electronic amplifier during the 1920s, which was important for long-distance telephony, required a higher signal-to-noise ratio, which was solved by negative feedback noise cancellation.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] This and other telephony applications contributed to the control theory.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] In the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flügge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic controls, which found military applications during the Second World War to fire control systems and aircraft navigation systems.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Controllers, which were able to make calculated changes in response to deviations from a set point rather than on-off control, began being introduced in the 1930s.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Controllers allowed manufacturing to continue showing productivity gains to offset the declining influence of factory electrification.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Factory productivity was greatly increased by electrification in the 1920s.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Alexander Field notes that spending on non-medical instruments increased significantly from 1929 to 1933 and remained strong thereafter.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The First and Second World Wars saw major advancements in the field of mass communication and signal processing.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Other key advances in automatic controls include differential equations, stability theory and system theory (1938), frequency domain analysis (1940), ship control (1950), and stochastic analysis (1941).
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] In 1959 Texaco's Port Arthur Refinery became the first chemical plant to use digital control.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Conversion of factories to digital control began to spread rapidly in the 1970s as the price of computer hardware fell.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The automatic telephone switchboard was introduced in 1892 along with dial telephones.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] By 1929, 31.9% of the Bell system was automatic.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Automatic telephone switching originally used vacuum tube amplifiers and electro-mechanical switches, which consumed a large amount of electricity.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Call volume eventually grew so fast that it was feared the telephone system would consume all electricity production, prompting Bell Labs to begin research on the transistor.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The logic performed by telephone switching relays was the inspiration for the digital computer.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The first commercially successful glass bottle-blowing machine was an automatic model introduced in 1905.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The machine, operated by a two-man crew working 12-hour shifts, could produce 17,280 bottles in 24 hours, compared to 2,880 bottles made by a crew of six men and boys working in a shop for a day.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The cost of making bottles by machine was 10 to 12 cents per gross compared to $1.80 per gross by the manual glassblowers and helpers.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives were developed using control theory.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives are used on different sections of a machine where a precise differential must be maintained between the sections.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] In steel rolling, the metal elongates as it passes through pairs of rollers, which must run at successively faster speeds.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] In paper making paper, the sheet shrinks as it passes around steam-heated drying arranged in groups, which must run at successively slower speeds.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The first application of a sectional electric drive was on a paper machine in 1919.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] One of the most important developments in the steel industry during the 20th century was continuous wide strip rolling, developed by Armco in 1928.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Before automation, many chemicals were made in batches.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] In 1930, with the widespread use of instruments and the emerging use of controllers, the founder of Dow Chemical Co. was advocating continuous production.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Self-acting machine tools that displaced hand dexterity so they could be operated by boys and unskilled laborers were developed by James Nasmyth in the 1840s.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Machine tools were automated with Numerical control (NC) using punched paper tape in the 1950s.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] This soon evolved into computerized numerical control (CNC).
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Today extensive automation is practiced in practically every type of manufacturing and assembly process.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Robots are especially useful in hazardous applications like automobile spray painting.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Robots are also used to assemble electronic circuit boards.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Automotive welding is done with robots and automatic welders are used in applications like pipelines.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] With the advent of the space age in 1957, controls design, particularly in the United States, turned away from the frequency-domain techniques of classical control theory and backed into the differential equation techniques of the late 19th century, which were couched in the time domain.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] During the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flugge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic control, which became widely used in hysteresis control systems such as navigation systems, fire-control systems, and electronics.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Through Flugge-Lotz and others, the modern era saw time-domain design for nonlinear systems (1961), navigation (1960), optimal control and estimation theory (1962), nonlinear control theory (1969), digital control and filtering theory (1974), and the personal computer (1983).
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Perhaps the most cited advantage of automation in industry is that it is associated with faster production and cheaper labor costs.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Another benefit could be that it replaces hard, physical, or monotonous work.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Additionally, tasks that take place in hazardous environments or that are otherwise beyond human capabilities can be done by machines, as machines can operate even under extreme temperatures or in atmospheres that are radioactive or toxic.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] They can also be maintained with simple quality checks.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] However, at the time being, not all tasks can be automated, and some tasks are more expensive to automate than others.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Initial costs of installing the machinery in factory settings are high, and failure to maintain a system could result in the loss of the product itself.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Automation primarily describes machines replacing human action, but it is also loosely associated with mechanization, machines replacing human labor.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The paradox of automation says that the more efficient the automated system, the more crucial the human contribution of the operators.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Humans are less involved, but their involvement becomes more critical.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Lisanne Bainbridge, a cognitive psychologist, identified these issues notably in her widely cited paper "Ironies of Automation." If an automated system has an error, it will multiply that error until it is fixed or shut down.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] A fatal example of this was Air France Flight 447, where a failure of automation put the pilots into a manual situation they were not prepared for.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Many roles for humans in industrial processes presently lie beyond the scope of automation.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Human-level pattern recognition, language comprehension, and language production ability are well beyond the capabilities of modern mechanical and computer systems (but see *Watson computer*).
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Tasks requiring subjective assessment or synthesis of complex sensory data, such as scents and sounds, as well as high-level tasks such as strategic planning, currently require human expertise.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] In many cases, the use of humans is more cost-effective than mechanical approaches even where the automation of industrial tasks is possible.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Therefore, algorithmic management as the digital rationalization of human labor instead of its substitution has emerged as an alternative technological strategy.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Overcoming these obstacles is a theorized path to post-scarcity economics.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] As of 2025-2026, real-world deployment of advanced robotics has revealed critical infrastructure limitations, such as "battery-life bottlenecks" (typically 2–4 hours of operation per charge) and the requirement for high-bandwidth Wi-Fi and specialized flooring for reliable function.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Additionally, robots continue to struggle with unpredictable human-made obstructions, which still necessitate human intervention to maintain operational flow.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Increased automation often causes workers to feel anxious about losing their jobs as technology renders their skills or experience unnecessary.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Early in the Industrial Revolution, when inventions like the steam engine were making some job categories expendable, workers forcefully resisted these changes.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Luddites, for instance, were English textile workers who protested the introduction of weaving machines by destroying them.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] More recently, some residents of Chandler, Arizona, have slashed tires and pelted rocks at a self-driving car, in protest over the cars' perceived threat to human safety and job prospects.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The relative anxiety about automation reflected in opinion polls seems to correlate closely with the strength of organized labor in that region or nation.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] According to one estimate, 47% of all current jobs in the US have the potential to be fully automated by 2033.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Furthermore, wages and educational attainment appear to be strongly negatively correlated with an occupation's risk of being automated.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Erik Brynjolfsson and Andrew McAfee argue that "there's never been a better time to be a worker with special skills or the right education, because these people can use technology to create and capture value.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Research by Carl Benedikt Frey and Michael Osborne of the Oxford Martin School argued that employees engaged in "tasks following well-defined procedures that can easily be performed by sophisticated algorithms" are at risk of displacement, and 47% of jobs in the US were at risk.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The study, released as a working paper in 2013 and published in 2017, predicted that automation would put low-paid physical occupations most at risk, by surveying a group of colleagues on their opinions.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] However, according to a study published in *McKinsey Quarterly* in 2015 the impact of computerization in most cases is not the replacement of employees but the automation of portions of the tasks they perform.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The methodology of the McKinsey study has been heavily criticized for being intransparent and relying on subjective assessments.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The methodology of Frey and Osborne has been subjected to criticism, as lacking evidence, historical awareness, or credible methodology.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Additionally, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) found that across the 21 OECD countries, 9% of jobs are automatable.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Based on a formula by Gilles Saint-Paul, an economist at Toulouse 1 University, the demand for unskilled human capital declines at a slower rate than the demand for skilled human capital increases.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] In the long run and for society as a whole it has led to cheaper products, lower average work hours, and new industries forming (i.e., robotics industries, computer industries, design industries).
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] These new industries provide many high salary skill-based jobs to the economy.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] By 2030, between 3 and 14 percent of the global workforce will be forced to switch job categories due to automation eliminating jobs in an entire sector.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] While the number of jobs lost to automation is often offset by jobs gained from technological advances, the same type of job loss is not the same one replaced and that leading to increasing unemployment in the lower-middle class.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] This occurs largely in the US and developed countries where technological advances contribute to higher demand for highly skilled labor but demand for middle-wage labor continues to fall.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Economists call this trend "income polarization" where unskilled labor wages are driven down and skilled labor is driven up and it is predicted to continue in developed economies.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Lights-out manufacturing is a production system with no human workers, to eliminate labor costs.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] It grew in popularity in the U.S. when General Motors in 1982 implemented humans "hands-off" manufacturing to "replace risk-averse bureaucracy with automation and robots".
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] However, the factory never reached full "lights out" status.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The costs of automation to the environment are different depending on the technology, product or engine automated.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] There are automated engines that consume more energy resources from the Earth in comparison with previous engines and vice versa.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Hazardous operations, such as oil refining, the manufacturing of industrial chemicals, and all forms of metal working, were always early contenders for automation.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The automation of vehicles could prove to have a substantial impact on the environment, although the nature of this impact could be beneficial or harmful depending on several factors.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Because automated vehicles are much less likely to get into accidents compared to human-driven vehicles, some precautions built into current models (such as anti-lock brakes or laminated glass) would not be required for self-driving versions.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Removal of these safety features reduces the weight of the vehicle, and coupled with more precise acceleration and braking, as well as fuel-efficient route mapping, can increase fuel economy and reduce emissions.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Despite this, some researchers theorize that an increase in the production of self-driving cars could lead to a boom in vehicle ownership and usage, which could potentially negate any environmental benefits of self-driving cars if they are used more frequently.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Automation of homes and home appliances is also thought to impact the environment.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] This study, along with others, indicated that the smart home's ability to monitor and adjust consumption levels would reduce unnecessary energy usage.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] However, some research suggests that smart homes might not be as efficient as non-automated homes.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] A more recent study has indicated that, while monitoring and adjusting consumption levels do decrease unnecessary energy use, this process requires monitoring systems that also consume an amount of energy.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The energy required to run these systems sometimes negates their benefits, resulting in little to no ecological benefit.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Another major shift in automation is the increased demand for flexibility and convertibility in manufacturing processes.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Manufacturers are increasingly demanding the ability to easily switch from manufacturing Product A to manufacturing Product B without having to completely rebuild the production lines.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Flexibility and distributed processes have led to the introduction of Automated Guided Vehicles with Natural Features Navigation.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Former analog-based instrumentation was replaced by digital equivalents which can be more accurate and flexible, and offer greater scope for more sophisticated configuration, parametrization, and operation.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] This was accompanied by the fieldbus revolution which provided a networked (i.e. a single cable) means of communicating between control systems and field-level instrumentation, eliminating hard-wiring.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Discrete manufacturing plants adopted these technologies fast.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The more conservative process industries with their longer plant life cycles have been slower to adopt and analog-based measurement and control still dominate.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The growing use of Industrial Ethernet on the factory floor is pushing these trends still further, enabling manufacturing plants to be integrated more tightly within the enterprise, via the internet if necessary.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Global competition has also increased demand for Reconfigurable Manufacturing Systems.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Engineers can now have numerical control over automated devices.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The result has been a rapidly expanding range of applications and human activities.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Computer-aided technologies (or CAx) now serve as the basis for mathematical and organizational tools used to create complex systems.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Notable examples of CAx include computer-aided design (CAD software) and computer-aided manufacturing (CAM software).
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The improved design, analysis, and manufacture of products enabled by CAx has been beneficial for industry.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Information technology, together with industrial machinery and processes, can assist in the design, implementation, and monitoring of control systems.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] One example of an industrial control system is a programmable logic controller (PLC).
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] PLCs are specialized hardened computers which are frequently used to synchronize the flow of inputs from (physical) sensors and events with the flow of outputs to actuators and events.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Human-machine interfaces (HMI) or computer human interfaces (CHI), formerly known as *man-machine interfaces*, are usually employed to communicate with PLCs and other computers.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Service personnel who monitor and control through HMIs can be called by different names.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] In the industrial process and manufacturing environments, they are called operators or something similar.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] In boiler houses and central utility departments, they are called *stationary engineers*.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Host simulation software (HSS) is a commonly used testing tool that is used to test the equipment software.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] HSS is used to test equipment performance concerning factory automation standards (timeouts, response time, processing time).
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Cognitive automation, as a subset of AI, is an emerging genus of automation enabled by cognitive computing.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Its primary concern is the automation of clerical tasks and workflows that consist of structuring unstructured data.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Cognitive automation relies on multiple disciplines: natural language processing, real-time computing, machine learning algorithms, big data analytics, and evidence-based learning.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Artificially intelligent computer-aided design (CAD) can use text-to-3D, image-to-3D, and video-to-3D to automate in 3D modeling.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] AI CAD libraries could also be developed using linked open data of schematics and diagrams.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Ai CAD assistants are used as tools to help streamline workflow.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Technologies like solar panels, wind turbines, and other renewable energy sources—together with smart grids, micro-grids, battery storage—can automate power production.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Many agricultural operations are automated with machinery and equipment to improve their diagnosis, decision-making and/or performing.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Agricultural automation can relieve the drudgery of agricultural work, improve the timeliness and precision of agricultural operations, raise productivity and resource-use efficiency, build resilience, and improve food quality and safety.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Increased productivity can free up labour, allowing agricultural households to spend more time elsewhere.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The technological evolution in agriculture has resulted in progressive shifts to digital equipment and robotics.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization using engine power automates the performance of agricultural operations such as ploughing and milking.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] With digital automation technologies, it also becomes possible to automate diagnosis and decision-making of agricultural operations.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] For example, autonomous crop robots can harvest and seed crops, while drones can gather information to help automate input application.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization has generally increased in recent years.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa is the only region where the adoption of motorized mechanization has stalled over the past decades.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Automation technologies are increasingly used for managing livestock, though evidence on adoption is lacking.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Adoption is likely mostly in Northern Europe, and likely almost absent in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Automated feeding machines for both cows and poultry also exist, but data and evidence regarding their adoption trends and drivers is likewise scarce.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Many supermarkets and even smaller stores are rapidly introducing self-checkout systems reducing the need for employing checkout workers.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] In the U.S., the retail industry employs 15.9 million people as of 2017 (around 1 in 9 Americans in the workforce).
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Globally, an estimated 192 million workers could be affected by automation according to research by Eurasia Group.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Online shopping could be considered a form of automated retail as the payment and checkout are through an automated online transaction processing system, with the share of online retail accounting jumping from 5.1% in 2011 to 8.3% in 2016.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] However, two-thirds of books, music, and films are now purchased online.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] In addition, automation and online shopping could reduce demands for shopping malls, and retail property, which in the United States is currently estimated to account for 31% of all commercial property or around 7 billion square feet (650 million square metres).
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Amazon has gained much of the growth in recent years for online shopping, accounting for half of the growth in online retail in 2016.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Other forms of automation can also be an integral part of online shopping, for example, the deployment of automated warehouse robotics such as that applied by Amazon using Kiva Systems.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The food retail industry has started to apply automation to the ordering process; McDonald's has introduced touch screen ordering and payment systems in many of its restaurants, reducing the need for as many cashier employees.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The University of Texas at Austin has introduced fully automated cafe retail locations.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Some cafes and restaurants have utilized mobile and tablet "apps" to make the ordering process more efficient by customers ordering and paying on their device.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Some restaurants have automated food delivery to tables of customers using a conveyor belt system.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The use of robots is sometimes employed to replace waiting staff.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Automation in construction is the combination of methods, processes, and systems that allow for greater machine autonomy in construction activities.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Construction automation may have multiple goals, including but not limited to, reducing jobsite injuries, decreasing activity completion times, and assisting with quality control and quality assurance.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Automated mining involves the removal of human labor from the mining process.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The mining industry is currently in the transition towards automation.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Currently, it can still require a large amount of human capital, particularly in the third world where labor costs are low so there is less incentive for increasing efficiency through automation.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) started the research and development of automated visual surveillance and monitoring (VSAM) program, between 1997 and 1999, and airborne video surveillance (AVS) programs, from 1998 to 2002.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Currently, there is a major effort underway in the vision community to develop a fully-automated tracking surveillance system.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Automated video surveillance monitors people and vehicles in real-time within a busy environment.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Existing automated surveillance systems are based on the environment they are primarily designed to observe, i.e., indoor, outdoor or airborne, the number of sensors that the automated system can handle and the mobility of sensors, i.e., stationary camera vs. mobile camera.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The purpose of a surveillance system is to record properties and trajectories of objects in a given area, generate warnings or notify the designated authorities in case of occurrence of particular events.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] As demands for safety and mobility have grown and technological possibilities have multiplied, interest in automation has grown.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Seeking to accelerate the development and introduction of fully automated vehicles and highways, the U.S.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Congress authorized more than $650 million over six years for intelligent transport systems (ITS) and demonstration projects in the 1991 *Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency Act* (ISTEA).
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Full automation commonly defined as requiring no control or very limited control by the driver; such automation would be accomplished through a combination of sensor, computer, and communications systems in vehicles and along the roadway.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Fully automated driving would, in theory, allow closer vehicle spacing and higher speeds, which could enhance traffic capacity in places where additional road building is physically impossible, politically unacceptable, or prohibitively expensive.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Automated controls also might enhance road safety by reducing the opportunity for driver error, which causes a large share of motor vehicle crashes.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Other potential benefits include improved air quality (as a result of more-efficient traffic flows), increased fuel economy, and spin-off technologies generated during research and development related to automated highway systems.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Automated waste collection trucks prevent the need for as many workers as well as easing the level of labor required to provide the service.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Business process automation (BPA) is the technology-enabled automation of complex business processes.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] It can help to streamline a business for simplicity, achieve digital transformation, increase service quality, improve service delivery or contain costs.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] BPA consists of integrating applications, restructuring labor resources and using software applications throughout the organization.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Robotic process automation (RPA; or RPAAI for self-guided RPA 2.0) is an emerging field within BPA and uses AI.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] BPAs can be implemented in a number of business areas including recruitment, marketing, sales and workflow.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Home automation (also called **domotics**) designates an emerging practice of increased automation of household appliances and features in residential dwellings, particularly through electronic means that allow for things impracticable, overly expensive or simply not possible in recent past decades.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The rise in the usage of home automation solutions has taken a turn reflecting the increased dependency of people on such automation solutions.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] However, the increased comfort that gets added through these automation solutions is remarkable.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Automation is essential for many scientific and clinical applications.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Therefore, automation has been extensively employed in laboratories.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] From as early as 1980 fully automated laboratories have already been working.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] However, automation has not become widespread in laboratories due to its high cost.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] This may change with the ability of integrating low-cost devices with standard laboratory equipment.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Autosamplers are common devices used in laboratory automation.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Logistics automation is the application of computer software or automated machinery to improve the efficiency of logistics operations.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Typically this refers to operations within a warehouse or distribution center, with broader tasks undertaken by supply chain engineering systems and enterprise resource planning systems.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Industrial automation deals primarily with the automation of manufacturing, quality control, and material handling processes.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] General-purpose controllers for industrial processes include programmable logic controllers, stand-alone I/O modules, and computers.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Industrial automation is to replace the human action and manual command-response activities with the use of mechanized equipment and logical programming commands.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] One trend is increased use of machine vision to provide automatic inspection and robot guidance functions, another is a continuing increase in the use of robots.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Industrial automation is simply required in industries.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The rise of industrial automation is directly tied to the "Fourth Industrial Revolution", which is better known now as Industry 4.0.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Originating from Germany, Industry 4.0 encompasses numerous devices, concepts, and machines, as well as the advancement of the industrial internet of things (IIoT).
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] An "Internet of Things is a seamless integration of diverse physical objects in the Internet through a virtual representation".
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] These new advancements have drawn attention to the world of automation and have shown ways for it to increase productivity and efficiency in machinery and manufacturing facilities.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 works with the IIoT and software/hardware to connect in a way that (through communication technologies) add enhancements and improve manufacturing processes.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Being able to create more advanced manufacturing is now possible with these new technologies.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] It opens up an improved manufacturing platform.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Implementation of systems such as SCADA is an example of software that takes place in industrial automation today.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] SCADA is a supervisory data collection software, just one of the many used in industrial automation.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 covers many areas in manufacturing.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Industrial robotics is a sub-branch in industrial automation that aids in various manufacturing processes.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Such manufacturing processes include machining, welding, painting, assembling and material handling to name a few.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Industrial robots use various mechanical, electrical as well as software systems to allow for high precision, accuracy and speed that far exceed any human performance.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The birth of industrial robots came shortly after World War II as the U.S. saw the need for a quicker way to produce industrial and consumer goods.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Servos, digital logic and solid-state electronics allowed engineers to build better and faster systems and over time these systems were improved and revised to the point where a single robot is capable of running 24 hours a day with little or no maintenance.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] In 1997, there were 700,000 industrial robots in use, the number has risen to 1.8M in 2017 In recent years, AI with robotics is also used in creating an automatic labeling solution, using robotic arms as the automatic label applicator, and AI for learning and detecting the products to be labelled.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Industrial automation incorporates programmable logic controllers in the manufacturing process.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) use a processing system which allows for variation of controls of inputs and outputs using simple programming.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] PLCs make use of programmable memory, storing instructions and functions like logic, sequencing, timing, counting, etc.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Using a logic-based language, a PLC can receive a variety of inputs and return a variety of logical outputs, the input devices being sensors and output devices being motors, valves, etc.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] PLCs are similar to computers, however, while computers are optimized for calculations, PLCs are optimized for control tasks and use in industrial environments.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] They are built so that only basic logic-based programming knowledge is needed and to handle vibrations, high temperatures, humidity, and noise.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The greatest advantage PLCs offer is their flexibility.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] With the same basic controllers, a PLC can operate a range of different control systems.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] PLCs make it unnecessary to rewire a system to change the control system.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] This flexibility leads to a cost-effective system for complex and varied control systems.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] PLCs can range from small "building brick" devices with tens of I/O in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with a count of thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] They can be designed for multiple arrangements of digital and analog inputs and outputs (I/O), extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Programs to control machine operation are typically stored in battery-backed-up or non-volatile memory.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] It was from the automotive industry in the United States that the PLC was born.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Before the PLC, control, sequencing, and safety interlock logic for manufacturing automobiles was mainly composed of relays, cam timers, drum sequencers, and dedicated closed-loop controllers.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Since these could number in the hundreds or even thousands, the process for updating such facilities for the yearly model change-over was very time-consuming and expensive, as electricians needed to individually rewire the relays to change their operational characteristics.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] When digital computers became available, being general-purpose programmable devices, they were soon applied to control sequential and combinatorial logic in industrial processes.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] However, these early computers required specialist programmers and stringent operating environmental control for temperature, cleanliness, and power quality.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] To meet these challenges, the PLC was developed with several key attributes.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] It would tolerate the shop-floor environment, it would support discrete (bit-form) input and output in an easily extensible manner, it would not require years of training to use, and it would permit its operation to be monitored.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Since many industrial processes have timescales easily addressed by millisecond response times, modern (fast, small, reliable) electronics greatly facilitate building reliable controllers, and performance could be traded off for reliability.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Agent-assisted automation refers to automation used by call center agents to handle customer inquiries.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The key benefit of agent-assisted automation is compliance and error-proofing.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] Agents are sometimes not fully trained or they forget or ignore key steps in the process.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] The use of automation ensures that what is supposed to happen on the call actually does, every time.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p01] There are two basic types: desktop automation and automated voice solutions.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] Fundamentally, there are two types of control loop: *open-loop control* (feedforward), and *closed-loop control* (feedback).
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] One of the simplest types of control is *on-off* control.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] An example is a thermostat used on household appliances which either open or close an electrical contact.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] Sequence control, in which a programmed sequence of *discrete* operations is performed, often based on system logic that involves system states.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] An elevator control system is an example of sequence control.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] A proportional–integral–derivative controller (PID controller) is a control loop feedback mechanism (controller) widely used in industrial control systems.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] The theoretical understanding and application date from the 1920s, and they are implemented in nearly all analog control systems; originally in mechanical controllers, and then using discrete electronics and latterly in industrial process computers.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] Sequential control may be either to a fixed sequence or to a logical one that will perform different actions depending on various system states.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] An example of an adjustable but otherwise fixed sequence is a timer on a lawn sprinkler.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] States refer to the various conditions that can occur in a use or sequence scenario of the system.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] An example is an elevator, which uses logic based on the system state to perform certain actions in response to its state and operator input.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] For example, if the operator presses the floor n button, the system will respond depending on whether the elevator is stopped or moving, going up or down, or if the door is open or closed, and other conditions.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] Early development of sequential control was relay logic, by which electrical relays engage electrical contacts which either start or interrupt power to a device.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] Relays were first used in telegraph networks before being developed for controlling other devices, such as when starting and stopping industrial-sized electric motors or opening and closing solenoid valves.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] Using relays for control purposes allowed event-driven control, where actions could be triggered out of sequence, in response to external events.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] These were more flexible in their response than the rigid single-sequence cam timers.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] More complicated examples involved maintaining safe sequences for devices such as swing bridge controls, where a lock bolt needed to be disengaged before the bridge could be moved, and the lock bolt could not be released until the safety gates had already been closed.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] The total number of relays and cam timers can number into the hundreds or even thousands in some factories.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] Early programming techniques and languages were needed to make such systems manageable, one of the first being ladder logic, where diagrams of the interconnected relays resembled the rungs of a ladder.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] Special computers called programmable logic controllers were later designed to replace these collections of hardware with a single, more easily re-programmed unit.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] In a typical hard-wired motor start and stop circuit (called a *control circuit*) a motor is started by pushing a "Start" or "Run" button that activates a pair of electrical relays.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] The "lock-in" relay locks in contacts that keep the control circuit energized when the push-button is released.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] (The start button is a normally open contact and the stop button is a normally closed contact.) Another relay energizes a switch that powers the device that throws the motor starter switch (three sets of contacts for three-phase industrial power) in the main power circuit.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] Large motors use high voltage and experience high in-rush current, making speed important in making and breaking contact.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] This can be dangerous for personnel and property with manual switches.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] The "lock-in" contacts in the start circuit and the main power contacts for the motor are held engaged by their respective electromagnets until a "stop" or "off" button is pressed, which de-energizes the lock in relay.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] Commonly interlocks are added to a control circuit.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] Suppose that the motor in the example is powering machinery that has a critical need for lubrication.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] In this case, an interlock could be added to ensure that the oil pump is running before the motor starts.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] Timers, limit switches, and electric eyes are other common elements in control circuits.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] Solenoid valves are widely used on compressed air or hydraulic fluid for powering actuators on mechanical components.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] Computers can perform both sequential control and feedback control, and typically a single computer will do both in an industrial application.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) are a type of special-purpose microprocessor that replaced many hardware components such as timers and drum sequencers used in relay logic–type systems.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] General-purpose process control computers have increasingly replaced stand-alone controllers, with a single computer able to perform the operations of hundreds of controllers.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] Process control computers can process data from a network of PLCs, instruments, and controllers to implement typical (such as PID) control of many individual variables or, in some cases, to implement complex control algorithms using multiple inputs and mathematical manipulations.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] They can also analyze data and create real-time graphical displays for operators and run reports for operators, engineers, and management.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] Control of an automated teller machine (ATM) is an example of an interactive process in which a computer will perform a logic-derived response to a user selection based on information retrieved from a networked database.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] The ATM process has similarities with other online transaction processes.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] The different logical responses are called *scenarios*.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] Such processes are typically designed with the aid of use cases and flowcharts, which guide the writing of the software code.
[src:autohotkey/automation-p02] The earliest feedback control mechanism was the water clock invented by Greek engineer Ctesibius (285–222 BC).
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] In computing, a **keyboard shortcut** (also **hotkey**/**hot key** or **key binding**) is a software-based assignment of an action to one or more keys on a computer keyboard.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] Most operating systems and applications come with a default set of keyboard shortcuts, some of which may be modified by the user in the settings.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] Keyboard configuration software allows users to create and assign macros to key combinations which can perform more complex sequences of actions.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] Some older keyboards had a physical macro key specifically for this purpose.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] The precise words used for these assignments and their meaning can vary depending on the context.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] For example, Microsoft has generally used *keyboard shortcuts* for Windows and Microsoft Office since the transition to 64-bit for Windows 7.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] However, they used *hot keys* prior to that and continue to do so in their 32-bit API for developing 'classic desktop apps'.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] Meanwhile, Lenovo and ASUS each have keyboard configuration software made for Windows that are named "Lenovo *Hotkeys*" and "ASUS Keyboard *Hotkeys*" respectively.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] The assignment process is referred to as *mapping* the actions to the keys, and changing them afterwards is therefore *remapping*.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] The assigned action is then said to be *bound* to the key, leading to the phrase *key binding* being used interchangeably with shortcut and hotkey.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] As other input devices became increasingly configurable in the early 2000's, the term *shortcut* began to be used to refer to what are essentially keyboard shortcuts being mapped to objects that are not keyboard keys.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] The most prevalent of these are computer mice, which went from only having two buttons for left and right clicks to having additional buttons on the around the side, top, and back of the mice (2-4 for common usage and up to 12 extra programmable buttons for certain types of gaming uses).
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] As Internet of things (IoT) devices continue to proliferate, *shortcuts* are appearing in many other device types such as electronic keyboards, home automation devices, wearable technology, and more.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] Human-computer interaction experts also continue to design new types of shortcuts altogether, such as gestures on touchscreens and touchless interfaces.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] Keyboard shortcuts are typically a means for invoking one or more commands using the keyboard that would otherwise be accessible only through a menu, a pointing device, different levels of a user interface, or via a command-line interface.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] Keyboard shortcuts are generally used to expedite common operations by reducing input sequences to a few keystrokes, hence the term "shortcut".
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] To differentiate from general keyboard input, most keyboard shortcuts require the user to press and hold several keys simultaneously or a sequence of keys one after the other.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] Unmodified key presses are sometimes accepted when the keyboard is not used for general input - such as with graphics packages e.g.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] Adobe Photoshop or IBM Lotus Freelance Graphics.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] Other keyboard shortcuts use function keys that are dedicated for use in shortcuts and may only require a single keypress.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] For simultaneous keyboard shortcuts, one usually first holds down the modifier key(s), then quickly presses and releases the regular (non-modifier) key, and finally releases the modifier key(s).
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] This distinction is important, as trying to press all the keys simultaneously will frequently either miss some of the modifier keys, or cause unwanted auto-repeat.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] Sequential shortcuts usually involve pressing and releasing a dedicated prefix key, such as the Esc key, followed by one or more keystrokes.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] Mnemonics are distinguishable from keyboard shortcuts.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] One difference between them is that the keyboard shortcuts are not localized on multi-language software but the mnemonics are generally localized to reflect the symbols and letters used in the specific locale.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] In most GUIs, a program's keyboard shortcuts are discoverable by browsing the program's menus – the shortcut is indicated next to the menu choice.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] There are keyboards that have the shortcuts for a particular application already marked on them.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] These keyboards are often used for editing video, audio, or graphics, as well as in software training courses.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] There are also stickers with shortcuts printed on them that can be applied to a regular keyboard.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] Reference cards intended to be propped up in the user's workspace also exist for many applications.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] In the past, when keyboard design was more standardized, it was common for computer books and magazines to print cards that were cut out, intended to be placed over the user's keyboard with the printed shortcuts noted next to the appropriate keys.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] When shortcuts are referred to as *key bindings,* it carries the connotation that the shortcuts are customizable to a user's preference and that program functions may be 'bound' to a different set of keystrokes instead of or in addition to the default.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] This highlights a difference in philosophy regarding shortcuts.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] Some systems, typically end-user-oriented systems such as Mac OS or Windows, consider standardized shortcuts essential to the environment's ease of use.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] In these commercial proprietary systems, the ability to change the default bindings and add custom ones can be limited, possibly even requiring a separate or third-party utility to perform the task, sometimes with workarounds like key remapping.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] In macOS, user can customize app shortcuts ("Key equivalents") in system settings, and customize text editing shortcuts by creating and editing related configuration files.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] Other systems, typically Unix and related, consider shortcuts to be a user's prerogative, and that they should be customizable to suit individual preference.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] In most real-world environments, both philosophies co-exist; a core set of *sacred* shortcuts remain fixed while others, typically involving an otherwise unused modifier key or keys, are under the user's control.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] The motivations for customizing key bindings vary.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] Users new to a program or software environment may customize the new environment's shortcuts to be similar to another environment with which they are more familiar.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] More advanced users may customize key bindings to better suit their workflow, adding shortcuts for their commonly used actions and possibly deleting or replacing bindings for less-used functions.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] Hardcore gamers often customize their key bindings in order to increase performance via faster reaction times.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] The original Macintosh User Interface Guidelines defined a set of keyboard shortcuts that would remain consistent across application programs.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] This provides a better user experience than the then-prevalent situation of applications using the same keys for different functions.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] This could result in user errors if one program used ⌘ Command+D to mean *Delete* while another used it to *Duplicate* an item.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] Later environments such as Microsoft Windows retain some of these bindings, while adding their own from alternate standards like Common User Access.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] The simplest keyboard shortcuts consist of only one key.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] For these, one generally just writes out the name of the key, as in the message "Press F1 for Help".
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] The name of the key is sometimes surrounded in brackets or similar characters.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] Many shortcuts require two or more keys to be pressed simultaneously.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] For these, the usual notation is to list the keys names separated by plus signs or hyphens.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] The Ctrl key is sometimes indicated by a caret character (^).
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] At times, usually on Unix platforms, the case of the second character is significant – if the character would normally require pressing the Shift key to type, then the Shift key is part of the shortcut e.g.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] Some keyboard shortcuts, including all shortcuts involving the Esc key, require keys (or sets of keys) to be pressed individually, in sequence.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] These shortcuts are sometimes written with the individual keys (or sets) separated by commas or semicolons.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] The Emacs text editor uses many such shortcuts, using a designated set of "prefix keys" such as Ctrl+C or Ctrl+X.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] Default Emacs keybindings include Ctrl+X Ctrl+S to save a file or Ctrl+X Ctrl+B to view a list of open buffers.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] Emacs uses the letter C to denote the Ctrl key, the letter S to denote the Shift key, and the letter M to denote the Meta key (commonly mapped to the Alt key on modern keyboards.) Thus, in Emacs parlance, the above shortcuts would be written C-x C-s and C-x C-b.
[src:autohotkey/keyboard-shortcut] A common backronym for Emacs is "Escape Meta Alt Ctrl Shift", poking fun at its use of many modifiers and extended shortcut sequences.
[src:autohotkey/v1] A special thanks to Jonathan Bennett, whose generosity in releasing AutoIt v2 as free software in 1999 served as an inspiration and time-saver for myself and many others worldwide.
[src:autohotkey/v1] In addition, many of AutoHotkey's enhancements to the AutoIt v2 command set, as well as the Window Spy and the old script compiler, were adapted directly from the AutoIt v3 source code.
[src:autohotkey/v1] So thanks to Jon and the other AutoIt authors for those as well.
[src:autohotkey/v1] Finally, AutoHotkey would not be what it is today without these other individuals.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The **Windows API**, informally **WinAPI**, is the foundational application programming interface (API) that allows a computer program to access the features of the Microsoft Windows operating system in which the program is running.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Programs typically access this API using system libraries, which are shared libraries.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Each major version of the Windows API has a distinct name that identifies a compatibility aspect of that version.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] For example, Win32 is the major version of Windows API that runs on 32-bit systems.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The name, Windows API, collectively refers to all versions of this capability of Windows.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Microsoft provides developer support via a software development kit, Microsoft Windows SDK, which includes documentation and tools for building software based on the Windows API.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] This section lists notable services provided by the Windows API.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Base services include features such as the file system, devices, processes, threads, and error handling.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] These functions reside in kernel.exe, krnl286.exe or krnl386.exe files on 16-bit Windows, and kernel32.dll and KernelBase.dll on 32 and 64 bit Windows.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] These files reside in the folder \Windows\System32 on all versions of Windows.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Advanced services include features beyond the kernel like the Windows registry, shutdown/restart the system (or abort), start/stop/create a Windows service, manage user accounts.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] These functions reside in advapi32.dll and advapires32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The Graphics Device Interface (GDI) component provides features to output graphics content to monitors, printers, and other output devices.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] It resides in gdi.exe on 16-bit Windows, and gdi32.dll on 32-bit Windows in user-mode.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Kernel-mode GDI support is provided by `win32k.sys` which communicates directly with the graphics driver.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The User Interface component provides features to create and manage screen windows and most basic controls, such as buttons and scrollbars, receive mouse and keyboard input, and other functions associated with the graphical user interface (GUI) part of Windows.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] This functional unit resides in user.exe on 16-bit Windows, and user32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Since Windows XP versions, the basic controls reside in comctl32.dll, together with the common controls (Common Control Library).
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The Common Dialog Box Library provides standard dialog boxes to open and save files, choose color and font, etc.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The library resides in a file called commdlg.dll on 16-bit Windows, and comdlg32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] It is grouped under the *User Interface* category of the API.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The Common Control Library provides access to advanced user interface controls, including things like status bars, progress bars, toolbars and tabs.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The library resides in a DLL file called commctrl.dll on 16-bit Windows, and comctl32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The Windows Shell component provides access to the operating system shell.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The component resides in shell.dll on 16-bit Windows, and shell32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The Shell Lightweight Utility Functions are in shlwapi.dll.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Network Services provide access to the various networking abilities of the operating system.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Its subcomponents include NetBIOS, Winsock, NetDDE, remote procedure call (RPC) and many more.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] This component resides in netapi32.dll on 32-bit Windows.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The Internet Explorer (IE) web browser exposes APIs and as such could be considered part of the Windows API.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] IE has been included with the operating system since Windows 95 OSR2 and has provided web-related services to applications since Windows 98.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The Windows API is a C language-based API.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Functions and data structures are consumable via C syntax by including windows.h, but the API can be consumed via any programming language that can inter-operate with the API data structures and calling conventions for function calls and callbacks.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Of note, the implementation of API functions has been developed in several languages other than C.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Despite the fact that C is not an object-oriented programming (OOP) language, the Windows API is somewhat object-oriented due to its use of handles.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Various other technologies from Microsoft and others make this object-oriented aspect more apparent by using an OOP language such as C++ — see Microsoft Foundation Class Library (MFC), Visual Component Library (VCL), GDI+.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Of note, Windows 8 provides the Windows API and the WinRT API, which is implemented in C++ and is object-oriented by design.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Windows.pas is a Delphi unit that exposes the features of Windows API – the Pascal equivalent of windows.h.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Many Microsoft technologies use the Windows API—as most software running on Windows does.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] As middle-ware between Windows API and an application, the following technologies provide some access to Windows API.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Some technologies are described as wrapping Windows API, but this is debatable since they don't provide or expose all of the capabilities of Windows API.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Although almost all Windows programs use the Windows API, on the Windows NT line of operating systems, programs that start early in the Windows startup process use the Native API instead.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The Windows API has always exposed a large part of the underlying structure of the Windows systems to programmers.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] This had the advantage of giving them much flexibility and power over their applications, but also creates great responsibility in how applications handle various low-level, sometimes tedious, operations that are associated with a graphical user interface.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] For example, a beginning C programmer will often write the simple "hello world" as their first assignment.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The working part of the program is only a single printf line within the main subroutine.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Charles Petzold, who wrote several books about programming for the Windows API, said: "The original hello world program in the Windows 1.0 SDK was a bit of a scandal.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] HELLO.C was about 150 lines long, and the HELLO.RC resource script had another 20 or so more lines.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] (...) Veteran programmers often curled up in horror or laughter when encountering the Windows hello-world program." Petzold explains that while it was the first Windows sample programs developers were introduced to, it was quite "fancy" and more complex than needed.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Tired of people ridiculing the length of the sample, he eventually reduced it to a simple MessageBox call.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Over the years, various changes and additions were made to Windows systems, and the Windows API changed and grew to reflect this.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The Windows API for Windows 1.0 supported fewer than 450 function calls, whereas modern versions of the Windows API support thousands.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] However, in general, the interface remained fairly consistent, and an old Windows 1.0 application will still look familiar to a programmer who is used to the modern Windows API.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Microsoft has made an effort to maintain backward compatibility.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] To achieve this, when developing new versions of Windows, Microsoft sometimes implemented workarounds to allow compatibility with third-party software that used the prior version in an undocumented or even inadvisable way.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Raymond Chen, a Microsoft developer who works on the Windows API, has said: "I could probably write for months solely about bad things apps do and what we had to do to get them to work again (often in spite of themselves).
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Which is why I get particularly furious when people accuse Microsoft of maliciously breaking applications during OS upgrades.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] One of the largest changes to the Windows API was the transition from Win16 (shipped in Windows 3.1 and older) to Win32 (Windows NT and Windows 95 and up).
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] While Win32 was originally introduced with Windows NT 3.1 and Win32s allowed use of a Win32 subset before Windows 95, it was not until Windows 95 that widespread porting of applications to Win32 began.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] To ease the transition, in Windows 95, for developers outside and inside Microsoft, a complex scheme of API thunks was used that could allow 32-bit code to call into 16-bit code (for most of Win16 APIs) and vice versa.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] *Flat thunks* allowed 32-bit code to call into 16-bit libraries, and the scheme was used extensively inside Windows 95's libraries to avoid porting the whole OS to Win32 in one batch.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] In Windows NT, the OS was pure 32-bit, except parts for compatibility with 16-bit applications, and only generic thunks were available to thunk from Win16 to Win32, as for Windows 95.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The Platform SDK shipped with a compiler that could produce the code needed for these thunks.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Versions of 64-bit Windows are also able to run 32-bit applications via WoW64.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The SysWOW64 folder located in the Windows folder on the OS drive contains several tools to support 32-bit applications.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Each version of Microsoft Windows contains a version of Windows API, and almost every new version of Microsoft Windows has introduced additions and changes to the Windows API.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The name, Windows API, refers to essentially the same capability in each version of Windows, but there is another name for this capability that is based on major architectural aspects of the Windows version that contains it.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] When there was only one version, it was simply called Windows API.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Then, when the first major update was made, Microsoft gave it the name Win32 and gave the first version the name Win16.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The term Windows API refers to both versions and all subsequently developed major versions.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The Wine project provides a Win32 API compatibility layer for Unix-like platforms, between Linux kernel API and programs written for the Windows API.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] ReactOS goes a step further and aims to implement the full Windows operating system, working closely with the Wine project to promote code re-use and compatibility.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] DosWin32 and HX DOS Extender are other projects which emulate the Windows API to allow executing simple Windows programs from a DOS command line.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Odin is a project to emulate Win32 on OS/2, superseding the original Win-OS/2 emulation which was based on Microsoft code.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Other minor implementations include the MEWEL and Zinc libraries which were intended to implement a subset of the Win16 API on DOS (see List of platform-independent GUI libraries).
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Windows Interface Source Environment (WISE) was a licensing program from Microsoft which allowed developers to recompile and run Windows-based applications on Unix and Macintosh platforms.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] WISE SDKs were based on an emulator of the Windows API that could run on those platforms.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] To develop software that uses the Windows API, a compiler must be able to use the Microsoft-specific DLLs listed above (COM-objects are outside Win32 and assume a certain vtable layout).
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The compiler must either handle the header files that expose the interior API function names, or supply such files.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] For the language C++, Zortech (later Symantec, then Digital Mars), Watcom and Borland have all produced well-known commercial compilers that have been used often with Win16, Win32s, and Win32.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Some of them supplied *memory extenders*, allowing Win32 programs to run on Win16 with Microsoft's redistributable Win32s DLL.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The Zortech compiler was probably one of the first stable and usable C++ compilers for Windows programming, before Microsoft had a C++ compiler.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] For certain classes of applications, the compiler system should also be able to handle interface description language (IDL) files.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Collectively, these prerequisites (compilers, tools, libraries, and headers) are known as the *Microsoft Platform SDK*.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] As of 2016, the MinGW and Cygwin projects also provide such an environment based on the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), using a stand-alone header file set, to make linking against the Win32-specific DLLs simple.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] LCC-Win32 is a C compiler maintained by Jacob Navia, freeware for non-commercial use.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Pelles C is a freeware C compiler maintained by Pelle Orinius.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Free Pascal is a free software Object Pascal compiler that supports the Windows API.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The MASM32 package is a mature project providing support for the Windows API under Microsoft Macro Assembler (MASM) by using custom made or converted headers and libraries from the Platform SDK.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Flat assembler FASM allows building Windows programs without using an external linker, even when running on Linux.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Windows specific compiler support is also needed for Structured Exception Handling (SEH).
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] This system serves two purposes: it provides a substrate on which language-specific exception handling can be implemented, and it is how the kernel notifies applications of exceptional conditions such as dereferencing an invalid pointer or stack overflow.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] The Microsoft/Borland C++ compilers had the ability to use this system as soon as it was introduced in Windows 95 and NT, however the actual implementation was undocumented and had to be reverse engineered for the Wine project and free compilers.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] SEH is based on pushing exception handler frames onto the stack, then adding them to a linked list stored in thread-local storage (the first field of the thread environment block).
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] When an exception is thrown, the kernel and base libraries unwind the stack running handlers and filters as they are encountered.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Eventually, every exception unhandled by the application will be dealt with by the default backstop handler, which pops up the Windows common crash dialog.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Microsoft has plans to update the Windows API for modern C++ usage with their `win32metadata` project.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Currently, there is C++/WinRT and "Windows Implementation Library" (WIL) for doing this in modern C++.
[src:autohotkey/windows-api] Microsoft has also created bindings for other languages, including C# and Rust for calling the Win32 API.
